The Preferences and settings for Process Designer can be edited in the preferences dialog. It is opened via the menu using the *Preferences* entry in the *Edit* category. On the left side of the dialog there is a tree containing the available preference pages. Click on an entry in the tree to display the corresponding page on the right side of the dialog. Page entries can have nested sub-entries, accessible by expanding the parent using the arrow left of it. A collapsible/expandable entry in the tree is a preference page as well as a container for other page entries. When changing preferences on a page, click the *Apply* button in the lower right corner to save them and keep the dialog open or the *OK* button below to save it and close the dialog. Click the *Restore Defaults* button of the page to reset all preferences of this page to their default values. This function is not available for all pages. Click the *Cancel* button to close the dialog and discard all unsaved changes.

## Execution
Contains settings for process executions.

*Max. number of log messages stored per execution*: Specifies a maximum number of log messages which the Process Designer will keep in memory for each process execution it tracks. Once the number of messages of an execution reaches this maximum, for each additional arriving message, the oldest one is deleted. Decreasing this number saves memory and reduces the maximum load of the *Log* view.

## General
Contains general settings for the Process Designer workbench.

- *Include SVG in process file* checkbox: If checked, an SVG image is generated and included in the metadata of the process file each time the process is saved.

- *Switch to test perspective on process launch* radio buttons: Defines if the workbench should switch to the the test perspective when a process execution is started from the Process Designer and the test perspective is not yet active. By default the application asks the user in form of a dialog each time. If the user selects the checkbox *Remember my decision* in the dialog, this preference is updated according to the decision.

- *Default Element Height* text field: Specifies the height a standard process element has when it is created in the editor. The default value is 85.

- *Default Element Width* text field: Specifies the width a standard process element has when it is created in the editor. The default value is 120.

## Layout
Contains settings which define the behaviour of the feature for automatic layout generation.

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 18. Layout Configuration Preference Page*

- *Trigger Layout on Group Collapse* checkbox: If checked, collapsing a group will apply an automatic layout to the whole process.

- *Process Orientation* radio buttons: Defines whether the process should be arranged from left to right (*horizontal*) or from top to bottom (*vertical*).

- *Space between Elements* fields: Control how much space should be left free between process elements horizontally and vertically.

- *Collapse Groups on Layout* checkbox: If checked, the automatic layout feature will collapse all groups in the process and generate the layout based on the collapsed elements.

- *Place states without connections* combo box: Defines where elements which are not connected to the main process flow should be placed, relative to the others.

## Process Engine
This page is used to integrate Process Engine instances into Process Designer. The list on the left side of the page shows all the existing Process Engine configurations. Process Engines can be added and removed using the *Add* and *Delete* buttons above the list. Select an entry in the list to display and modify the configurations preferences on the right side of the page.

The *Config Name* text field at the top defines the name of this configuration. It must be unique within the configurations in this list. This is the name which will be used when you need to specify a Process Engine in the main workbench toolbar or the *Launch Configurations *dialog.

The *Test Engine* button at the bottom can be used to test if a working Process Engine can be found under the specified location. The managed version needs to start up the soap service, which might take a few seconds. Once the test is done a dialog will pop up either with a success message and the version of the Process Engine if it was found or an error message if it failed. While the test is in progress, the button changes to *cancel* and can be used to stop the test.

The area between The *Config Name* field and the *Test Engine* button contains three tabs which can be used to define different parts of the Process Engine Configuration. These tabs are described in the following chapters.

### Details
The *Details* tab contains the basic information which is required in order to connect to a

Process Engine. The first field is the combo box *Type* which can be used to select the type of Process Engine to configure. Changing the selection alters the visibility of some of the controls below.

There are three types of Process Engines configurations:

**remote**

An externally running Process Engine which can be reached by the Process Designer via SOAP or REST calls. Requires the base URI under which the Process Engine can be reached. If the scheme of the Base URI is rest, the REST API will be used for communicating with the Engine, if the scheme is soap the SOAP API will be used. If the scheme is http, the Process Designer will pick SOAP or REST if either is available.

**managed**

A local command line installation of the Process Engine which will be started as standalone webservice by the Process Designer. Requires a path to the folder where the main .jar file of the installation is located and a free port under which the webservice should be made available. A managed configuration must be start by the user via the corresponding button in the toolbar of the main workbench, before it is accessible. Once the managed Engine is not used anymore it should be stopped with the same button.

**cluster**

This type is similar to remote, with the difference that it expects multiple Process

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 19. Process Engine Configuration Preference Page: Remote Engine*

![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 20. Process Engine Configuration Preference Page: Managed Engine*

Below the *Type* combo box the following fields can be available, depending on the type selection:

- *Base URI* text field: Only available for *remote*. Defines the base URI of the remote Process Engine Webservice.

- *Path* text field: Only available for *managed*. Defines the location of a local Engine installation.

- *Browse* button: Only available for *managed*. Select Engine installation directory from the file system and insert its path into the *Path* field.

- *Port* field: Only available for *managed*. Defines the port for starting the webservice.

- *Nodes* field: Only available for *cluster*. Defines a list of Process Engine base URIs for the individual nodes in a cluster, separated by line breaks.

- *Load Balancer* combo box: Only available for *cluster*. Defines the load balancing mechanism for deciding how requests are distributed between the cluster nodes.

- *Process Baspath* text field: Optional. Defines a path relative to the process engine base directory to use as base directory for process executions.

- *Task Manager* text field: Optional. Provides a URL to the SOAP or REST endpoint of a

Task Manager. This Task Manager is used for loading the Task Types for the Editor Palette. If it is empty, the endpoint will be queried from the Process Engine. This field is mainly intended to be used when the Task Manager configured in a Process Engine is not reachable under the same URL from Process Designer (e.g. under localhost), but it can also be used to connect to a Task Manager which is not associated with the Process Engine.

### Credentials
The *Credentials* tab can be used to define credentials for a user under which the configured

Process Engine should be accessed. These credentials will be used for loading the Activity Modules and Task types for the editor palette. By default they are also used for executing processes, unless the launch configuration defines its own credentials.

In order to specify credentials, an authentication type must be selected. This can be done manually, by choosing one of the options from the drop down menu. If a valid URL has been provided, the *Detect* button to the right of the drop down can be used to automatically find out what kind of authentication the server requests. The area below is dynamically filled with input fields specific to the authentication type when the selection changes. Some types have advanced fields, which are only visible when the *Advanced* check box is checked.

### Message Queue
If the Process Engine is configured for message logging, this tab can be used to provide the settings for receiving log messages via message queue. If the check box *Use Message Queue *is checked, Process Designer will try to connect to the message queue if one is provided by the configured Process Engine. The other fields in this tab are only active when the checkbox is checked. In the field *Logging Topic* the correct name of the message topic, which the log messages are written to, must be provided. If no topic name was specified for the message logger in the Process Engine configuration file, this can be left empty, otherwise it has to be the same name as used in the configuration file. If the Message Queue requires authentication, a username and password also need to be provided.

> Warning

If the check box *Use Message Queue* is checked but the Process Engine is not configured for message logging or the message queue is not reachable, processes executed by this Engine will not be updated correctly in Process Designer when the state of the execution changes.

## Resource Explorer
This page contains settings for the integrated Resource Explorer, used for all file dialogs and in the *Resource Explorer* view. Has two sub-entries *Columns* and *Hosts*. For information regarding Resource Explorer and its settings please consult the Resource Explorer documentation.

## Style
![](data:image/png;base64,)*Figure 21. Style Preference Page*

Contains settings regarding the visual representation of elements in the process diagram.

In the *Element Colors* section the colour for process element types can be configured. For each element there are two colours which can be set. The left colour field for the header, the right one for the body. The colour can be changed by clicking on a colour field and selecting the preferred colour from the colour dialog. Either select a basic colour from the list or click on *Add Custom Colors* to open the panel for custom colour configuration and define a colour. Once the colour is selected click *OK* to set the colour or cancel to keep the old one. Apply the colour preferences to adopt the colours in the process diagram.
